{"annotations": [{"id": ["NCBIGene:2796"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GnRH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9873201847076416, "span": {"begin": 0, "end": 4}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "porcine", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9895073771476746, "span": {"begin": 23, "end": 30}}, {"id": ["mesh:C081916"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "pGlu-His-Trp-Ser-Tyr-Gly-Leu-Arg-Pro-Gly", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996715784072876, "span": {"begin": 94, "end": 134}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2796"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GnRH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.991787850856781, "span": {"begin": 180, "end": 184}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2796"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GnRH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9891701340675354, "span": {"begin": 233, "end": 237}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2796"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GnRH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9947673082351685, "span": {"begin": 332, "end": 336}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9964355230331421, "span": {"begin": 353, "end": 355}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2796"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GnRH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9921324849128723, "span": {"begin": 450, "end": 454}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2796"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GnRH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9927933216094971, "span": {"begin": 573, "end": 577}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2796"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GnRH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9832080006599426, "span": {"begin": 602, "end": 606}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 701, "end": 703}}], "text": "GnRH was isolated from porcine hypothalamus. It was structurally identified as a decapeptide (pGlu-His-Trp-Ser-Tyr-Gly-Leu-Arg-Pro-Gly&middot;N et al., 971). During the childhood, GnRH levels are low but as&nbsp;puberty&nbsp;begins. GnRH levels start to rise and when the&nbsp;testes&nbsp;and&nbsp;ovaries&nbsp;are fully developed. GnRH regulates &nbsp;LH and these hormones to control the production of sex hormones in adult (Marques et al., 2018). GnRH secretion have been described in pulsatile (in minutes) and surge modes. Pulsatile mode refers to episodic release of GnRH while the surge mode of GnRH secretion occurs in females during the pre-ovulatory phase (Maeda et al., 2010). Secretion of LH is also in pulsatile nature ( in hrs)(Bolt, 1971).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:55:57 +0000 2026"}